04651nam a22007335i 9780292739147DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011049722  a97802927391477 a10.7560/7391302doi  a(DE-B1597)587452  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aHD9734.M42bT88 2012 4aHD9734.M42 ǂb T88 2012eb 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a331.4097211 aTuttle, Carolyn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMexican Women in American Factories :bFree Trade and Exploitation on the Border /cCarolyn Tuttle. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (253 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures, Tables, and Boxes -- tList of Abbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. American Factories in Mexico -- t2. The Border City of Nogales -- t3. House to House: The Method of Analysis -- t4. The History of the Maquila Industry -- t5. Are the Maquilas Sweatshops? -- t6. Liberation or Exploitation of Women Workers? -- t7. Fancy Factories and Dilapidated Dwellings -- tAppendix 1. Maquilas in Nogales, Sonora, 2004 -- tAppendix 2. Survey of Maquila Workers -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrior to the millennium, economists and policy makers argued that free trade between the United States and Mexico would benefit both Americans and Mexicans. They believed that NAFTA would be a “win-win” proposition that would offer U.S. companies new markets for their products and Mexicans the hope of living in a more developed country with the modern conveniences of wealthier nations. Blending rigorous economic and statistical analysis with concern for the people affected, Mexican Women in American Factories offers the first assessment of whether NAFTA has fulfilled these expectations by examining its socioeconomic impact on workers in a Mexican border town. Carolyn Tuttle led a group that interviewed 620 women maquila workers in Nogales, Sonora, Mexico. The responses from this representative sample refute many of the hopeful predictions made by scholars before NAFTA and reveal instead that little has improved for maquila workers. The women’s stories make it plain that free trade has created more low-paying jobs in sweatshops where workers are exploited. Families of maquila workers live in one- or two-room houses with no running water, no drainage, and no heat. The multinational companies who operate the maquilas consistently break Mexican labor laws by requiring women to work more than nine hours a day, six days a week, without medical benefits, while the minimum wage they pay workers is insufficient to feed their families. These findings will make a crucial contribution to debates over free trade, CAFTA-DR, and the impact of globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCorporations, ForeignzMexico. 0aInternational business enterpriseszUnited StatesxEmployees. 0aManufacturing industrieszUnited StatesxEmployees. 0aOffshore assembly industryzMexico. 0aWomen offshore assembly industry workerszMexico 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73913040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292739147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292739147/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK